In certain groups of mites—including those with parasitic larvae (e.g., Parasitengona) and others (e.g., 
Astigmata, Uropodina
) in which the deutonymph is specialized for dispersal (
Krantz & Walter 2009
; 
Walter & Proctor 2013
)— juvenile instars long have been of great interest, and in some cases may be better known than the adult. But for most mites the focus has been on adults, with ontogeny being poorly known or ignored altogether. Recent attempts to narrow this gap have included a series of special 
Zootaxa
volumes dedicated to ontogenetic studies (
Zhang 2023
).

